  "pr_comment_markdown": "## Crucible Review Summary\n\n- Issues: 12\n- Critical: 2, Warning: 7\n\n### Top Actions\n- [Critical] Missing success confirmation and startup logging before uvicorn.run() (factory/cli.py:973)\n- [Critical] Missing server startup confirmation message (factory/cli.py:973)\n- [Warning] Short flag -h for --host violates help convention (factory/cli.py:955)\n- [Warning] Short flag -h for --host violates universal help convention (factory/cli.py:955)\n- [Warning] Lazy import of uvicorn contradicts hard dependency status and delays error detection (factory/cli.py:963)\n- [Warning] Inconsistent dependency pattern: lazy import contradicts hard dependency declaration (factory/cli.py:963)\n- [Warning] Missing type hints, docstrings, response models, and API metadata (factory/server.py:1)\n- [Warning] Missing test coverage for ImportError handling path (tests/test_cli_serve.py:45)\n- [Warning] Missing test coverage for uvicorn ImportError handling path (tests/test_cli_serve.py:45)\n\n### Notable Issues\n- **Missing success confirmation and startup logging before uvicorn.run()** `factory/cli.py:973`: The serve() function validates port, handles ImportError, then directly calls uvicorn.run() without any typer.echo() output. Users receive no indication that the server is starting or confirmation of successful startup. uvicorn.run() is a blocking call; after it succeeds, control never returns. This creates poor UX: users can't distinguish between 'server is starting' and 'process hung' without external monitoring. For port 0 (ephemeral allocation), users have no way to discover which port the OS allocated. Missing confirmation pattern contrasts with typical CLI servers (nginx, redis, etc.) that print 'listening on 0.0.0.0:8000'.\n- **Missing server startup confirmation message** `factory/cli.py:973`: The serve() function validates arguments and imports dependencies, then directly calls uvicorn.run() without any user-facing output. Users cannot distinguish between 'server is starting' and 'process hung', and for port 0 (ephemeral allocation), users cannot discover the assigned port. This creates poor UX compared to standard CLI servers (nginx, redis, etc.) that print listening address on startup.\n- **Short flag -h for --host violates help convention** `factory/cli.py:955`: Line 955 defines -h as short flag for --host option. This violates the universal Unix/CLI convention where -h means --help. Users intuitively expect 'factory serve -h' to display help text, not set the host. While typer's argument parser handles this precedence gracefully (--help takes precedence in help context, -h resolves to --host in command context), this creates cognitive friction and violates conventions. Every CLI tool uses -h for help, so breaking this pattern surprises users and damages discoverability.\n- **Short flag -h for --host violates universal help convention** `factory/cli.py:955`: Line 955 defines -h as short flag for --host option, violating the universal Unix/CLI convention where -h means --help. Users intuitively expect 'factory serve -h' to display help text. While typer handles this gracefully internally, this pattern breaks user expectations and damages discoverability. Every CLI tool uses -h for help.\n- **Lazy import of uvicorn contradicts hard dependency status and delays error detection** `factory/cli.py:963`: uvicorn and factory.server are imported inside the serve() function (lines 963-964), creating false impression that these are optional dependencies. However, pyproject.toml lists fastapi and uvicorn as hard dependencies (not under [project.optional-dependencies]), required for all installations. This violates Python convention: hard dependencies should be imported at module level so ImportError occurs at package load time (enabling detection by tools like pip-audit, mypy), not at runtime when user invokes the command. Pattern contradicts codebase intent to make HTTP API a core feature. Additionally, ImportError is caught and handled (lines 964-966), which is appropriate ONLY for truly optional dependencies. The lazy import + error handling pattern creates inconsistency with the hard dependency declaration.\n- **Inconsistent dependency pattern: lazy import contradicts hard dependency declaration** `factory/cli.py:963`: uvicorn is imported inside serve() with try/except ImportError handling (lines 963-967), signaling optional dependency. However, pyproject.toml declares fastapi>=0.100 and uvicorn>=0.23 as hard dependencies, required for all installations. This inconsistency violates Python convention where hard dependencies are imported at module level. The lazy import + error handling pattern is appropriate only for truly optional dependencies. Additionally, this hides import errors from tools like pip-audit and mypy until serve() is invoked. Root cause: unclear whether HTTP API is core feature (hard dependency) or optional (should be in [project.optional-dependencies]).\n- **Missing type hints, docstrings, response models, and API metadata** `factory/server.py:1`: factory/server.py lacks basic documentation and type safety: (1) No module-level docstring explaining purpose or API intent; (2) hello() function has no return type hint (should declare -> Dict[str, str] or Pydantic model); (3) No function docstring describing endpoint behavior; (4) FastAPI app initialized with no title, description, or version, so auto-generated OpenAPI docs (/docs endpoint) will be generic and unhelpful; (5) No Pydantic response model for schema validation and IDE autocomplete; (6) Hardcoded endpoint in module with no routing structure established for future expansion. As API grows (status, control endpoints), this module will become unmaintainable.\n- **Missing test coverage for ImportError handling path** `tests/test_cli_serve.py:45`: Test suite includes mocks for uvicorn.run() success and OSError/Exception failures, but does NOT test the ImportError handling path (lines 964-966 in cli.py) that was added for defensive programming. The try/except for 'import uvicorn' should have at least one test case that verifies the error message when uvicorn is not available. Without this test, the ImportError path is untested and regressions could go unnoticed. This is especially important for optional dependency patterns.\n- **Missing test coverage for uvicorn ImportError handling path** `tests/test_cli_serve.py:45`: Test suite covers uvicorn.run() success/failure cases (OSError, Exception) but does NOT test the ImportError handling path (factory/cli.py lines 964-966) that was added for defensive programming. Without coverage of this error path, regressions could go unnoticed, especially important if lazy import pattern is retained for optional dependency pattern.\n- **Hard dependency on fastapi/uvicorn increases deployment footprint for CLI-only users** `pyproject.toml:16`: fastapi>=0.100 and uvicorn>=0.23 are now required for all factory installations (lines 16-17), even if users only use the CLI orchestration features and never invoke the HTTP server. This increases package size, installation time, and potential vulnerability surface. Compare with slack-sdk, which is properly moved to [project.optional-dependencies] and is only required for users who invoke the slack-listen command. If the HTTP API is truly optional or not core to the factory mission, these dependencies should be moved to optional-dependencies with the name 'api' or 'server'.\n",
